Whenever I speak in public (and no matter what I say), there is a torrent of insults on social networks that call for “good-bye,” denouncing the center’s policies, telling me that I should not belong to the Labour Party.
And I'm not the only one going through this.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the comments that are addressed to me tend to be of a political nature.
I am amazed by the professionalism and determination of these colleagues who face a barrage of sexist or racist insults every day, but who never back down from them.
One of the aspects that disappoints me most in this era of politics is the way these levels of insult have become normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we have ceased to be inclusive, and with each motion of "censorship" or change in the rules of selection the party narrows its views.
I have received countless advice over the past two years urging me to keep my head down, not to be so expressive, and that it would “be all right” for me.
But that's not why I came here to do politics.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student, driven by the negligence of the Thatcher government that left my comprehensive school classroom literally in ruins, I have sought to fight for better public services for those who need them most, whether as mayor or as a minister in the government.
I have never hidden my policies, including in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could have been in any way confused as to my political positions and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who promoted the motion on Friday, all I have to say is that when the country is heading for a Brexit that will hurt families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on the issue of my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in fact, the message I have is not for the Nottingham Momentum; it is for my constituents, members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threats of “dismissal” or political expedients will prevent me from acting in the sense of what I believe to be the interests of all of you.
