North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were exacerbating mistrust of the United States and that there was no way the country could unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons in those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test center and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
“However, we do not see any corresponding U.S. response,” he said.
“Without trust in the U.S., there will be no trust in our national security and under such circumstances there is no way we can proceed with our disarmament first.”
Although Ri has recycled well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in so far as they do not outright reject the earlier unilateral, contrasting Pydong.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the prolongation of sanctions is compounding our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: “If the party interested in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this deadlock.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s rockets toward U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. President Mau” Trump called Kim the “man of the rockets” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea’s denuclearization.
