Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our Almanac "Sunday Morning": On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today and continues to count ... was born in Germany the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A fundamental piece of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become a central element of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" in which unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans participated:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals like uranium.
When we put these headphones on, we can even hear the effects of atoms released by radioactivity on minerals.”
Evans: "Look, it's really cracking now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention to which he gave the name still endures.
New Cancer Vaccine Teaches Immune System to ‘See’ Harmful Cells
