Vaccine Teaches Immune System to Recognize Harmful Cells as Part of Treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their alteration in the laboratory
These cells, which can “see” a protein common to many cancers, are then injected back into the body.
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a range of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, has seen her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their alteration in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, designated by HER2. These cells are then injected into the body again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results suggest we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of various types of cancer," including breast, ovarian, lung, and colorectal cancers, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach involving removing immune cells from patients and “teaching” them to attack cancer cells worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
