Red Tide Update: Concentrations Decline in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in Red Tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower spread of spots in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties were identified, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Sea spotted extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
Last week, mean concentrations were recorded near or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background concentrations at high concentrations in Manatee County, background concentrations at high concentrations near or off the coast of Sarasota County, background concentrations at high concentrations in Charlotte County, and background concentrations at high concentrations in Charlotte County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwest Florida region.
